California Housing Set¶

The idea here is similar to what I was doing with the Boston Housing dataset (predicting the median value of homes in a district). In this instance, rather than focus on implementing an optimization algorithm, I try to learn to replicate the kinds of things that an actual ML engineer might do on a day-to-day basis.

Most of this work is taken straight from Aurelien Geron's "Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras & TensorFlow". Although, I did add my own touch with this method, the results of which can be seen below.

I just started working with this dataset (Feb/1/2023). In the near future I'll probably try to come up with my own prediction model and spend some time fine-tuning it.

import os
import tarfile
import urllib
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

DOWNLOAD_ROOT = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ageron/handson-ml2/master/"
HOUSING_PATH = os.path.join("datasets", "housing")
HOUSING_URL = DOWNLOAD_ROOT + "datasets/housing/housing.tgz"

def fetch_housing_data(housing_url=HOUSING_URL, housing_path=HOUSING_PATH):
    os.makedirs(housing_path, exist_ok=True)
    tgz_path = os.path.join(housing_path, "housing.tgz")
    urllib.request.urlretruieve(housing_url, tgz_path)
    housing_tgz = tarfile.open(tgz_path)
    housing_tgz.extractall(path=housing_path)
    housing_tgz.close()

def load_housing_data(housing_path=HOUSING_PATH):
    csv_path = os.path.join(housing_path, "housing.csv")
    return pd.read_csv(csv_path)

# using a hashing algorithm to ensure that we get the same test set even if the dataset gets updated
from zlib import crc32
def test_set_check(identifier, test_ratio):
    return crc32(np.int64(identifier)) & 0xffffffff < test_ratio * 2**32

def split_train_test_by_id(data, test_ratio, id_column):
    ids = data[id_column]
    in_test_set = ids.apply(lambda id_: test_set_check(id_, test_ratio))
    return data.loc[~in_test_set], data.loc[in_test_set]

# returns a subset of df in which all the values of var fall between min and max inclusive
def get_attribute_range(X, col, min, max):
    return X[(X[:, col] >= min) & (X[:, col] <= max)]

data-cleaning method¶

In [ ]:
from math import floor, ceil

def remove_caps(df, col, step, sensitivity=4, num_iters=2):
    
    if sensitivity < 0 or sensitivity > 10:
        raise Exception
    threshold = list(range(10, 0, -1))[sensitivity]

    for _ in range(num_iters):
        min_ = floor(df.min(axis=0)[col])
        max_ = ceil(df.max(axis=0)[col])
        min_range = np.arange(min_, max_ - step, step)
        max_range = np.arange(min_ + step + 1, max_, step)
        for i, j in zip(min_range, max_range):
            if max_ - j < step:
                j = max_
            frame = df[(df[col] >= i) & (df[col] <= j)]
            grouped = frame.groupby([col]).size()
            std_dev = grouped / np.std(grouped)
            for elem in grouped[std_dev > threshold].index:
                df = df[df[col] != elem]
    return df

housing_cleaned = housing.copy()

housing_cleaned = remove_caps(housing, 'median_house_value', step=10000, sensitivity=4)

from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

rooms_ix, bedrooms_ix, population_ix, households_ix = 3, 4, 5, 6

class CombinedAttributesAdder(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    def __init__(self, add_bedrooms_per_room=True):  # no *args or **kargs
        self.add_bedrooms_per_room = add_bedrooms_per_room
    
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self     # nothing to do here
    
    def transform(self, X):
        rooms_per_household = X[:, rooms_ix] / X[:, households_ix]
        population_per_household = X[:, population_ix] / X[:, households_ix]
        if self.add_bedrooms_per_room:
            bedrooms_per_room = X[:, bedrooms_ix] / X[:, rooms_ix]
            return np.c_[X, rooms_per_household, population_per_household, bedrooms_per_room]
        else:
            return np.c_[X, rooms_per_household, population_per_household]

attr_adder = CombinedAttributesAdder(add_bedrooms_per_room=False)
housing_extra_attribs = attr_adder.transform(housing.values)
In [ ]:
median_house_value_ix = 8

class RemoveCaps(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):

    def __init__(self, step:int=10000, sensitivity:int=4, num_iters:int=2):
        self.step=step
        self.sensitivity=sensitivity
        self.num_iters=num_iters
    
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self     # nothing to do here
    
    def transform(self, X):
        if self.sensitivity < 0 or self.sensitivity > 10:
            raise Exception('senisitivity must be and integer between 0 and 10 (inclusive)')
        threshold = list(range(10, 0, -1))[self.sensitivity]

        for _ in range(self.num_iters):
            sup_min = floor(np.amin(X[:, median_house_value_ix]))
            sup_max = ceil(np.amax(X[:, median_house_value_ix]))
            min_range = np.arange(sup_min, sup_max - self.step, self.step)
            max_range = np.arange(sup_min + self.step + 1, sup_max, self.step)
            for min_, max_ in zip(min_range, max_range):
                if sup_max - max_ < self.step:
                    max_ = sup_max
                slice_ = get_attribute_range(X, median_house_value_ix, min_, max_)
                unique = np.unique(slice_[:, median_house_value_ix])
                frequencies = [np.sum(slice_[:, median_house_value_ix] == unique_elem) for unique_elem in unique]
                avg = np.mean(frequencies)
                std = np.std(frequencies)
                if std == 0:
                    above_threshold_index = np.array([True for _ in unique])
                else:
                    above_threshold_index = (frequencies - avg) / std > threshold
                for elem in unique[above_threshold_index]:
                    X = X[X[:, median_house_value_ix] != elem]
        return X
